 src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  What, and more importantly, WHY</span><hr size=1> OK...thanks for all the responses, as promised I'll throw my own 2 cents in now as well.<br>
<br>
Everyone mentioned that they draw the line at things that would harm someone else in some way.  And, CAD said she thought this might be a weird one on her part, but I liked how she put it:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Irresponsible sex. When the person just has sex and doesn't think about any of the precautions or ramifications of their actions - putting sex and their own gratification before anything or anyone else.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think there are a couple of levels where sex crosses into &quot;harming.&quot;  First, even if that actual act doesn't end up hurting someone else, if it was done for gratifiaciton first and foremost being put before anything else I think that is selfish and harmful at least the the person being selfish.  I think we have some pretty strong drives and that it is beneficial for our own sense of well being as well as for those around us when we are able to have some self discipline (in a healthy way, I don't think being &quot;up tight&quot; about sex is the same as having a healthy discipline over our drives).<br>
<br>
Second, I think the power to bring another human life into being is an incredible gift and resposibility.  I think sometimes it is easy to forget that this is an inherent part of sex, not just a side note to the physical gratification.  The responses of arousal are all to facilitate intercourse (lubrication, erections, etc, sorry if this is too detailed for some) which can lead to conception.  I think there is something inherently &quot;harmful&quot; again to our own well being as well as to that of the other person to neglect this aspect.  I've used this comparison before, to forget what an awesome power that comes along with sex is like treating your fine china like it's tupperware.  It shows a lack of appreciation for what it truly is.<br>
<br>
Third, and IMO the most important thing is to remember the third life that might be created by the act.  You know what we all say, the only birth control that is %100 effective is abstinence.  I think to have sex with a person and in a situation where you have no intention of supporting a child and each other in raising that child is not &quot;responsible&quot;.<br>
<br>
Now...I know we could all argue about what really counts as harmful and why, but that explains fairly simplisticly where I'm coming from on the issue, and why I think God has some strict regulations on what is considered inappropriate or not.  I read what DBC said about sin, and as usual I agree with a lot of what he said, but I usually credit the misuse of religion to man, not to God.  He is well intentioned in his guidance for us, it is humans who mess it up.  There is even a verse in LDS scripture about that, maybe I'll go dig it up and edit it in.<br>
<br>
Anyway...so, for all those reasons listed above I think that the only appropriate sex is done with appropriate appreciation and respect for procreation in it's entirety (which certainly does include physical pleasure among many other wonderful things) inside a marriage.<br>
<br>
Well...speaking of procreation, my baby is getting fussy <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  so I'll have to elaborate more later, if anyone is interested I guess <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
